      there's an EDM thing that people do sometimes. let's say you have a full-blown dance beat going, with 4-on-the-floor kick, and you have some heavy compression applied so that all the other instruments duck way down in volume whenever the kick hits. Then, imagine taking out the kick but somehow make it so the rest of the sound is still ducking in that pulse. so now you have a kick shaped hole in the music, on all the downbeats

12.8.22  2:11 pm   the argument that saying "this apple is similar" and "are we in a simulation" is the same since you're not clarifying what the other thing is is not valid because simulation is a noun and similar is an adjective

      that's not the basis of the analogy. the basis of the analogy was that they both require a partner. actually, to play into your love of grammar, i might add that they both specifically seem to require a prepositional phrase, in that instance. i can also give you another example of how a noun+preposition can behave exactly the same way as adj+preposition: if you say you are "a fan of" something, or if you say you are "wild about" something. on paper, "a fan" appears to be a noun, and "wild" appears to be an adjective, and yet i think you can see that those phrases seem to occupy the exact same grammatical real estate

     When the guy finally gets the rabbit out of the hat he is sent to the wasteland by the narrator as punishment. 

     as i recall, the rabbit, the house, the table, and most things, disappeared at the moment the rabbit was presumed to be IN the hat. not out of the hat. as i recall, it was "put the rabbit back in the hat", we see the rabbit go back in the hat, then there's some announcements, then everything disappears except the hat and the earth, and the person
